{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_hiko_ver01/data/sn86076249/00332891364/1908020801/0132.xml":{"full_text":"CUMBERLAND ELY AND NEVADA CONSOLIDATED ARE BIGGER THAN BUTTE-IN NATURAL RAILROAD AND SMELTING CENTER\n[eut WTTTTF PTNP [ely\nY? Mil M I\u2019J _L Hi I '1 i 1 \"revjsaa:1\nESTABLISHEDIN 1868. ELY, WHITE PINE COUNTY, NEVADA, SATURDAY, FEBRUARY 8, 1908. ifluE'x *-\u00abINTH YEAR\nDETAILS OF NEVADA CONS.\u2019\nBOND ISSUE ARRANGEMENT\nMAKE IT ATTRACTIVE\nLife of Bonds is Ten Years\u2014May be Exchanged\nFor Stock of Company at any Time Within Five\nYears\u2014Entire Issue Is Underwritten Through\nTripp Co.\u2014Was Four Times Oversubscribed.\nThe details of tile plan of the bond issue ol' Nevada 'onsolidaled as\nauthorized at the meeting of stock holders of the compuny Ihthiiu- known\nhere yesterday through u telegram from W. II. Thompson. The telegram\nfollow s:\n\u2022\u2022The ImumIs authorized are for $.1,000,000. They are ten year, six\nper cent convertible gold Isolds, to he of date of April I, I (MIX. Interest\nIs payable April I and October 1. The Hankers* Trust Co. Is named as\ntrustee.\n\u201cStoekholder* of record on February 17 are accorded the privilege\nof sulmcribing according to their stock holdings. Payment* as arranged\nfor the Isolds are o in*-half on or lief ore March IO and I lie balance on or\nbefore April 20.\n\u201cTin* ImumIs may is* converted into stock of the Nevada Consolidated\nat tin* rate of $10 |x*r share al any time within live years from date of\nissue.\n\u201cThe entire issue of ImumIs has been underwritten by Trlp|s* X To.,\nsyndicate managers, acting for a group of banker*. Applications for priv\nilege to participate in the underwriting cxc\u00ab*edcd in anion ills of money\noffer**1 four time* the amount of the bond Issue.\u201d\nr\nThe investment opporlunity offered under the ulsive arrangement is\nconsidered very attractive Imally. With the mines of the company in the\nsplendid shape that they are known to Is* among |M*ople here and with\nrailroad eommunlentiow established xvAvI* the concentrator, wlricli is now\n\\ailhin a comparatively few days of readiness to commence work on the\n;{0 years* supply of ore which Nevada <'ousolidated has blin ked out and\non the immense tonnage which CiimlN\u2019rlaiid Fly has in readiness liesidc\nthe higher grade which It will send divert to smelter, Nevada Consol idal'sl\nIiMik* exceedingly good for dividend* long before the fund which the\nIk,ml issue will put In its treasury Is exhausted. It will also Is- a very\ngreat surprise if the bond holder cannot within five year* trade his bond*\nin for stock of tin* company worth several times its present value per\nshare iu the market.\nThe readiness with which the bond Issue was underwritten and tin*\navidit> wP* which capital sought oppor unify to participate i.t i.der\nwriting is a feature that s|s*aks exceedingly high fur not only the confi\ndence entertained in Nevada Consol Ida ted hut also highly f<o the confi\ndence which is felt in the district. It is money that counts and plainly\nthen* is no hesitation on its part in associating itself with the enterprises\nof the allied interests in this camp.\nMAW 1TTFMITH MARK\nTO WKKCK X.-O.-l'. TIIAI\\\nNevada, ('allfnrnia and Oregon Line\nOffer* Reward for rapture\nnf Offender*.\nRKNO, Keh. 7 Rally attempt*, it\ndevelop*, have prevailed for some\ntime to wreck the Nevada, California\nand Oregon railroad express that\nruns from Likely to Reno. T he man\nagement has offered a reward of $-'00\nfor the capture of the perpetrators.\nTrack walkers have discovered rails\nplaced across the track at dangerous\npoints, and at other places boulders\nhave been dropped where the train,\nin passing a curve, would lie wreck\ned. The nmllng of the obstruction\npinioned to the rails at High Mot\nSprings trestle caused the official* to\nplace watchmen along the track\nJAM ART INIMRIMRATIOXM\nTHK I.OW KST FOR Iff TFAIIS\nTotal Capitali/utiim in Fast Only\nffiMI, I 50,000\u2014October, 1004,\nOne Kxceptton.\nNKW YORK, Fell. 7. Incorpora\ntions In the eastern states during\nJanuary aggregated the smallest to\ntal of any month In the last 15 years,\nwith one exception. The total capi\ntalization of the companies formed\nIn the states of New Jersey, New\nYork, Delaware and Maine, with a\ncapital of $1,080,000 or more, as re\nported to the New York Commercial,\nwas $:!!!,150,000. There is no par\nallel for lids small investment, ex\ncept in the month of October, 1 904,\nwhen the total capitalization of the\ncompanies formed was hut $20,700,\n000.\nIn January, 1907, the amount rep\nresented by the Incorporation of new\ncompanies was more thun $200,000,\n000, greater than the total of this\nmonth, and m January, 190G, the\ntotal was over $125,000,000 greater.\nFollowing the panic of October and\nNovember, the new incorporations\nfell to low proportions, lint the total\nof November and December each was\ntwice as great us the total for tills\nmonth. In the months Immediately\nfollowing the panic of 1902 there\nwas some curtailment In the amount\nof capital represented by the com\npanies taking out papers In the vari\nous states, but the totals then fnr ex\nceeded the meagre amount of this\nmonth.\nNEED SIDEWALKS\nTO ELY DEPOT\nAn effort will be made ut tin* next\nmeeting of the Ely dry council to\nhave the Nevada Northern railway\ntrains run fact her than the depot\ninto the town with their new subur\nban service trains At present no\nsuch action is probable on tin* part\nof the railway company, as it has\nbeen announced that trains will start\nfrom tin* depot.\nAnother matter of somewhat sim\nilar nature will he brought up. that\nof providing some temporary walks\nor other method for allowing per\nsons coming from McQill or those\nwishing to visit the smelter site, a\nchance to walk dryshod between\nGarden and Aultman streets.\nAt present this portion of the walk\nbetween the station and the main\nstreet of Ely is a perfect lob-lolly of\n'slimy mud and none can cross it\nwithout experiencing the unpleasant\nsensation of wet feet.\nMayor Clark was interviewed yes\nterday by a News representative on\nthe subject to see if something along\nthis line could not be done before\nthe first train is run tomorrow, but\nhe stated that he could do nothing\nwithout consent of the council. It j\nIs possible that If the trains are not 1\nrun farther into Ely than the depot,\nseveral wagon loads of cinders will\nbe procured and spread on the path\nways to ensure dryness under foot.\nReward Ottered tor\nMissing Man\nWith no clue to the whereabouts\nof Hutchinson Stevens, who disap\npeared December 6, 1007, Ills broth\ners in Lovelock have advertised n re\nward of $400 for information lead\ning to the finding of the man. who\nis supposed to have wmide/ed off\nfrom the summit between American\ncanyon and Limerick canyon, several\nmiles from Lovelock, after doing\nsome assessment work on claims\n1 here.\nStevens, the missing man, is de\nscribed as five feet 10 inches tall, and\nweight ISO pounds. He Is aO years\nold and has a heavy mustache. One!\nupper front tooth 1ms been broken;\noff. At the time of his disappearance\nhe wore a brown khaki suit.\nSheriff Davis has received notifi\ncation of the reward, wliich has been\nsent to all towns in the state.\n\u201cNOW IS THE TIME\u201d\nCLASSIFYING OF LICENSES\nIS ENGAGING ATTENTION\nOne of the matters which will\ndoubtless l\u00bbe brought to the atten\ntion of the city council in the near\nfuture is that of license classifica\ntion. At present the small merchants\nof Ely are paying the same amount to\nconduct their business as are mer\nchants who do many times the\namount of trade.\nUp to the present the same condi\ntion of affairs has been evident in\ncounty license paying, no segregation\nhaving been made. Sheriff Davis is\nnow giving tills matter his attention\nand the licenses are being segregat\ned as it -on sennence. the man doing\na large buitncai Itstrtoi to pa; a\nlarger license than the small busi\nness man.\nOne instance of the injustice of\nthe present condition is that a man\nconducting a small establishment,\nlike a street lunch stand, is forced to\npay the same amount for license that\na restaurant proprietor has to pay,\nwhile a person having two rooms for\nrent ranks with a lodging house\nkeeper*, and a small lodging house\nranks with a hotel.\nA plan has been suggested, and\nwhen the matter Is brought up will\nprobably be followed. It is proposed\nthat each merchant shall render an\naccurate statement of business done\nat his establishment during a stated\nperiod. According to these state\nments. which may be verified hv per\nsonal inspection of the books of the\nconcern by the license collector, the\nlicenses would he issued.\nThe plan is without doubt a good\none and will probably meet with ap\nproval of both the merchants and\ncity officials\nTersely of Rawhide\nThis Elyite Tells\nThe first letter received here which\ntold anything of the conditions at\nRawhide other than that it was a\ncamp of expectation was received\nyesterday by M. Kerman of the Step\ntoe hotel barber shop from P. J.\nKiicullen, who left here several\nweeks ago.\nKiicullen is perhaps as enthusias\ntic in his writing as any of the men\nwho have previously written hut his\nletter tells more in detail of the act\nual condition of the camp than any\nprevious ones.\n\u201cYou had better come over and see\nit for yourself,\u201d he writes. \u201cI never\nsaw anything like the free gold sur\nface showing before in my life, nor\nso many enthusiastic people. If it\ngoes as it now looks it is the greatest\nin the world, and well worth the time\nand money to come and see it.\u201d\nFurther Kiicullen states that the\npopulation is now more than 3,000\nand is increasing from 50 to 100 per\nsons each day. Two miles of tents\nand shack streets are already laid\nout. There are 35 saloons, 15 res\ntaurants and four newspapers now in\noperation.\nPrices are high, as is usual in gold\ncamps, especially new ones. Water\ncosts ihe consumer $2 a barrel.\nWood sells for $30 a cord. Coal\nbrings the dealer $50 a ton and peo\nple are glad to gef it at that. Lum\nber for building purposes brings high\nprices from $60 to $110 a thousand\nfeet, being the usual rates. Reds anti\ncots cost the lodger one dollar a\nnight. Fating is more reasonable,\nprices averaging about the same as\nin Klv.\nThe writer expresses his intention\nof remaining in the new Golconda\nand in ending his letter urges Mr.\nHerman to \u201ccome over and get in in\ntime.\nAs the first statement of condi\ntions. as far as living expenses are\nconcerned, the letter is valuable, es\npecially to those intending to go to i\nRawhide, as they will now know\nwhat to expect upon arrival there.\nIS VKItY IIX.\nCar! Stevens, aged 15, is very ill\nat the home of his mother on Auit\ninan street, having a Severe attack of\npneumonia. At present his condition\nis considered very serious and some\nfears for Ills recovery are entertain\ned. The father of the young man\ndied last spring from effects of tu\nberculosis. Young Stevens, brother,\nwho is working in the White River\ndistrict, has been notified of his con\ndition and is expected to arrive here\ntoday.\nNIX AND PHEBYS\nBUY AT RAWAIDE\nGeorge H. Nix, F. S. and Joseph\nI Pheby, during the week purchased\nfrom ('onrad Anderson a group of\nI fi*\u2022' lainis located at Rawhide by\nhim. The price paid cannot be as\ncertained. .Mr. Anderson arrived\n(here last week, bringing with him\nsamples of ore running from $r\u00bbo to\n500 in gold and carrying silver val\nlies. The deal was put through on\n'these samples and the statements of\ni the seller.\nF. S. Pheby left here t riday morn\ning for Rawhide to examine the\nproperty and report to his associates,\nas well as to look over the camp with\nthe idea of further investment.\nIf his reports are favorable it is j\nprobable that the claims will be In\ncorporated Into a company and the:\nstock floated locally for development\nof the ground. Anderson states that\nIt lies in a portion of the camp con\nsidered most promising in view of!\npast finds.\nCompany is Formed\nTo go After Oil\nArticles of incorporation for the!\nNevada Home Oil company, capital\nized at $1,000,000, with principal\nplace of business at Reno, were filed\nyesterday with the \u2019county clerk\nLife of the corporation is unlimited.\nThe objects of the company will\nbe to buy. acquire, lease, or other\nwise get control of oil lands, and to\ndevelop the petroleum, natural gas,\noil, asphaltum or other products of,\nthe ground and to place it upon the j\nmarket. They also retain the right\nto build refineries, own pipe lines and\nany other property necessary to car\nry on their business.\nThe capitalization of the company\nis divided into one million shares of\npart value of $1 each, of which 250.-.\n000 shares have been subscribed al\nready. The incorporators are J.\nAaron Ingalls of Wadsworth. Nov.,\nwith 124,000 shares; J. M. Prouty of\nReno, Nev., 124,000 shares, and E (i.\nProuty, 1,000 shares. None of this\nstock is actually paid up.\nThe directors of the company will\nbe five in number, none having been\nnamed as yet. While the principal\noffice of the company is to be located\nat Reno, the company reserves the'\ni\nEagles Will Try For\nProminent Visitor\nEfforts are being made to gpt\n(fraud Worthy President Theodore\nHell of the Fraternal Order of Eagles\nto come to Ely when he speaks in\nReno to the lodge there on the loth\nof this month, but nothing definite\nhas yet been heard from him, and\nlocal members of the order are un\ncertain whether he will come here or\nnot.\nPresident Hell is especially inter\nesting to the public because of the\nradical action he Is adopting in clean\ning the pages of lodge rolls of drones,\nwho neither work in other places nor\nwill lie of benefit to the order.\nA short lime since he sent forth\nhis fiat declaring ngab st the prac\ntice of admitting members nut cred\nitable to tlte order and to enforce his\nidea dissolved one lodge which failed\nto come itii to the Ideal standard lie\nhas fixed.\nOn account of the personality of\nthe man he is arousing much interest\namong outsiders as well as members\nof the lodge. It lias not been an\nnounced whether, in rase he comes to\nEly, tlte meeting lie will address will\nlie open to the public or purely for\nlodge men.\nright to establish offices at such\nother places both in this and other\nstates and In foreign countries as in\ntheir judgment are necessary.\nWithin the last few weeks several\ncompanies with large capitalization\nhave been organized in tlte state or\nhave been organized in other states,\nfiling their articles of incorporation\nhere. Whether this concern is to\nhave a local office cannot tie ascer\ntained at present.\nFor more than six months pros\npectors in the employ of this concern\nhave been locating oil bearing lauds\nill the vicinity of illipuh siding. Sev\neral discoveries of bituminous shale\nand surface oil have been made with\nin the last few years. Eighty petro\nleum locations have been acquired\nby the representatives. Within a\nShort time lulling for oil will begin\nas arrangements are reported to lie\nunder way for installation of drills\nwith which to sink.\nFrom surface indications there\nseems to lie little doubt that the drills\nwill encounter something which will\nmore than fulfill the expectations of\nthe holding coriioratlon.\nThe McNamara mine at Tonopah is\nshipping ore from a seven foot ledge\nThe ore by a little sorting runs near\nly *300.\nTRADE SHOWS IMPROVIDENT\nNEW TRAINS EXPECTED\nTO HELP MATERIALLY\nI am looking forward to a much\nbrighter business future for Ely.\nwhen the regular train service be\ntween Ely and McCiill is established,\u201d\nsaid V. R. Lewis, the druggist, yes\nterday. Even the small crowd\nwhich came up Thursday night to at\ntend the Eagles\u2019 dance brought a\nlarge amount of business for us. and\nl suppose for many stores around\nthe town.\n\u201cThe business outlook is becoming\nincreasingly bright with us and\nnothing lias made us fee! so much\nheartened as the manner in which\ntrade improved, even with the small\nnumber of persons coming up Thurs\nGIROUX ISSUE\nOF $1,500,000\nIN BONDS\nPropose Getting of Water\nFor Mill and Making\nMine and Surface Im\nprovements with Fund\nThe first news of authentic char\nacter was received yesterday from\nNew York with reference to the\nGiroux Consolidated. It confirmed\nprevious rumor that $1,000,000 in\nbonds will be issued by the company,\n4he money to be applied to develop\nment of the mine and putting of the\nconcentrator of the company in ser\nvice.\nJoseph Giroux, according to the\ntelegram, retains his control of the\naffairs of the* corporation in spite of\nefforts of stockholders to oust him.\nThis was expected locally, as he with\nbis brother holds (jO per cent of the\n1 Giroux Consolidated stock and oust\ning them from control was not be\nlieved possible.\nWith the $1,000,000 to be secured\nj by IkhhI flotation it is proposed to\nadd another unit to the mill of the\nj company,, which will give them am\npie facilities for outputting large\nj amounts of concentrates. New board\ning bouse facilities, newT offices and\nnew buildings for alcove ground ac\nj commodatlons are also proposed.\nIt is further claimed that the town\ni site proposition of the company,\nj which has hitherto been held back on\nj account of lack of sufficient funds to\nj carry it through to successful con\ni elusion, will be again placed on foot.\nAll these improvements will natur\nally carry with them an increase of\nforce. The proposition therefore\nj sounds very good to local people.\nA further plan which is rumored\nwill be building of a pipe line from\nt the .Mungerson ranch, where the com\npany owns a valuable water right, to\nthe concentrator to provide ample\nsupply of water for running the#\nplant. A portion of the water used\nwill be, it is known, supplied by the\nAlpha, which is a wet shaft. Gen\nerally speaking, it Is not considered\nprobable that this will make suffi\ncient. water to operate the mill, a con\nclusion which the pipe line scheme\nwould indicate the company to have\nalso reached.\nKMKJI l*:\\T DIVINK IXttllNG.\nTO SA( lti;i> HKAHT CHI ItCII\n0_\nWill Participate in Impressive 4\u2019aitli\nolic Ceremony\u2014Special Music.\nAnnouncement is made of services\nto be held In Sacred Heart Catholic\ni hurcli on the fifth Sunday after the\nKphiphany, which are of unusual in\nI terest. First mass will be held at\nj S a. in.. Father W. K. Ryan, cele\nbrant. Second mass, which will I** a\nj high mass, will be held at 10:30, at\nwhich a sermon will be delivered by\nRev. Father W. K. Ryan of St.\nMary's cathedral. Salt Lake, who is\nwidely known as an eloquent speaker,\nin the evening at 7:30 one of the\ni most beautiful and solemn eeremon\nies of the church, the canonic erec\ntion of the station of the cross, will\noccur.\nThe choir, under the direction of\nMrs. Frank Xevin, will render a gro\ngram arranged for this ceremony,\nand Father Ryan will give a lucid\nand interesting explanation of it.\nday. i am confident that all mer\nchants will feel appreciably the ef\nfect of increase in trade which will\nbe brought about by the daily train\nservice.'\u2019\nF. M. Clark of the Clark drug\n\u2022store stated yesterday that the week\nhas been one during which his busi\nness wus constantly Increasing.\n\"Itmslness fins grown much better,\nfully 2b per cent improvement in the\nlust seven days, 1 should say.\u201d\nKvery other merchant spoken to\non the subject expressed the opinton\nthat the service will aid Kly business\nmen to a great extent and all look\nforward to better times.","height":"23380","width":"16036"}}
